. Some forms of Christianity itself might seem alien, so the book also considers the interface between traditional Catholicism, new forms of Protestantism, and Greek and Russian orthodoxy. But it also finds that the concept of Christendom was under threat in other places, some much nearer to home. Edges of Christendom could be found in areas that were or had been pagan, such as Rome itself and the Danelaw, which once covered northern England; they could even be found in English homes and gardens, where imported foreign flowers and exotic new ingredients challenged the concept of what was native and natural.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aBorders.  aCatholicism.  aChristendom.  aEurope.  aGardens.0 cEPUBz97815015141730 cprintz978150152033440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150151415940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501514159423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501514159/original  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK